# Environment Setup (Node, Git, VS Code)

Ensure a recent LTS of Node.js is installed (see [Node.js official site](https://nodejs.org)【16†L11-L19】).  You can download and install Node.js (LTS) and Git, then open your project in an editor like VS Code.  Initialize a new project directory (e.g. `npm init -y`) and install only the needed libraries: for example, the official guide suggests using the `express` web framework and a lightweight WebSocket library (`ws`)【25†L206-L214】.  In your shell, you might run:
```
npm install express ws
``` 
These will give you an HTTP server and a WebSocket server, with no build step or extra frameworks required.  

# server.js – Express HTTP Server + WebSocket

In **server.js**, create an Express app that serves your static files and also accepts WebSocket connections.  For example, use `express.static` to serve `index.html`, `style.css`, and `app.js` from a `public` folder (or the same folder)【22†L63-L72】【26†L1-L4】:
```js
const express = require('express');
const { createServer } = require('http');
const { WebSocketServer } = require('ws');

const app = express();
// Serve static files (index.html, style.css, app.js, etc.)
app.use(express.static(__dirname));  // or path.join(__dirname, 'public')

// Create an HTTP server and attach Express
const httpServer = createServer(app);

// Attach WebSocket server on the same HTTP server (shares the port)【29†L166-L174】【25†L258-L264】
const wss = new WebSocketServer({ server: httpServer });

// Example: handle WebSocket connections
wss.on('connection', (ws) => {
  console.log('Client connected via WebSocket');
  ws.send(JSON.stringify({ type: 'init', message: 'Connected to Master Cockpit' }));

  // Handle incoming messages from the client
  ws.on('message', (data) => {
    const msg = JSON.parse(data);
    console.log('Received from client:', msg);
    // (You can handle actions like initSwarm, runPipeline, etc., here)
    // For this demo, simply echo back:
    wss.clients.forEach(client => {
      if (client.readyState === ws.OPEN) {
        client.send(JSON.stringify({ type: 'echo', original: msg }));
      }
    });
  });
});
```
Finally, have the server listen on port 3001 and bind to `0.0.0.0` (to accept external VPS traffic). For example:
```js
const PORT = 3001;
httpServer.listen(PORT, '0.0.0.0', () => {
  console.log(`Server listening on port ${PORT}`);
});
```
This sets up a simple Express+WebSocket server. The use of `ws` (a fast, minimal WebSocket library) is recommended in Node.js guides【25†L206-L214】, and attaching it to the HTTP server lets you serve pages and handle live updates on the same port【25†L258-L264】.  

