# app.js – Client Logic & Simulation

In **app.js**, open a WebSocket to your server and handle real-time updates. For example:
```js
// Connect to WebSocket (ws:// for HTTP or wss:// for HTTPS)
const protocol = window.location.protocol === 'https:' ? 'wss:' : 'ws:';
const socket = new WebSocket(`${protocol}//${window.location.host}`);

socket.addEventListener('open', () => {
  console.log('WebSocket connected');
  logEvent('[SYSTEM] Connected to cockpit server');
});

// Handle incoming messages (data from server)
socket.addEventListener('message', (event) => {
  const msg = JSON.parse(event.data);
  console.log('Received', msg);
  if (msg.type === 'init') {
    logEvent('[SYSTEM] ' + msg.message);
  } 
  else if (msg.type === 'metrics') {
    updateMetrics(msg);
  } 
  else if (msg.type === 'swarm') {
    renderSwarm(msg.nodes);
  }
  else if (msg.type === 'agents') {
    renderAgents(msg.agents);
  }
  else if (msg.type === 'pipelineResult') {
    appendLog('pipelineResults', `[${new Date().toLocaleTimeString()}] ${msg.details}`);
  }
  else if (msg.type === 'testResult') {
    appendLog('testResults', `[${new Date(msg.timestamp).toLocaleTimeString()}] ${msg.name}: ${msg.status}`);
  }
  else if (msg.type === 'healEvent') {
    appendLog('healLog', msg.event);
    logEvent('[HEAL] ' + msg.event);
  }
  else if (msg.type === 'echo') {
    // example of echoed action, ignore or handle if needed
  }
});

// Send an action to the server
function send(obj) {
  socket.send(JSON.stringify(obj));
}

// Utility: log to the master event log
function logEvent(text) {
  const log = document.getElementById('eventLog');
  log.textContent = `[${new Date().toLocaleTimeString()}] ${text}\n` + log.textContent;
}
function appendLog(id, text) {
  const log = document.getElementById(id);
  log.textContent = text + "\n" + log.textContent;
}

// Update metric displays in Master tab
function updateMetrics(data) {
  document.getElementById('agentsActive').textContent = data.agentsActive;
  document.getElementById('swarmNodes').textContent = data.swarmNodes;
  document.getElementById('jobsCompleted').textContent = data.completed;
  document.getElementById('errors').textContent = data.errors;
  document.getElementById('cpuUsage').textContent = data.cpu;
  document.getElementById('memUsage').textContent = data.memory;
  document.getElementById('diskUsage').textContent = data.disk;
}

// Render swarm nodes in Swarm tab
function renderSwarm(nodes) {
  const nodeList = document.getElementById('nodeList');
  nodeList.innerHTML = '';
  nodes.forEach(n => {
    const div = document.createElement('div');
    div.textContent = `${n.id}: ${n.agents} agents, ${n.tasks} tasks [${n.status}]`;
    nodeList.appendChild(div);
  });
}

// Render agent status in Agents tab
function renderAgents(agents) {
  const agentList = document.getElementById('agentList');
  agentList.innerHTML = '';
  agents.forEach(a => {
    const div = document.createElement('div');
    div.textContent = `${a.name}: ${a.status}, CPU ${a.cpu}%, Mem ${a.memory}%`;
    agentList.appendChild(div);
  });
}

// Tab switching logic
function showTab(name) {
  document.querySelectorAll('.tab-content').forEach(tab => {
    tab.style.display = (tab.id === name ? 'block' : 'none');
  });
}
```
This client script listens for WebSocket messages from the server and updates the DOM accordingly.  You’ll need to implement the matching logic in the server (e.g. when the server has new metrics or node/agent data, it should send a JSON message like `{type:'metrics', cpu:..., agentsActive:..., ...}` which the client handles).  The above code shows how to handle various message types and update the UI. 

In particular, this code uses a `logEvent` function to record system events (similar to the “Event Log” in your cockpit). It also has `appendLog` to add lines to the pipeline/test/heal logs. The HTML has corresponding `<pre>` elements with the IDs `eventLog`, `pipelineResults`, `testResults`, and `healLog` that we append lines to. 

# Simulating Live Data and Actions

To make the dashboard “alive,” the server can simulate data and push updates over the WebSocket. For example, inside your **server.js** you might maintain state objects for agents, swarm nodes, test results, etc., and then periodically update and broadcast them:

```js
// Example: initial state
let agents = [
  {id:'kilo', name:'Kilo (Master)', status:'running', cpu:45, memory:62, tasks:8, completed:1247, errors:0},
  {id:'lingma', name:'Lingma (Research)', status:'running', cpu:38, memory:55, tasks:3, completed:892, errors:0},
  /* ... other agents ... */
];
let swarmNodes = [];  // will be filled on init
let totalCompleted = 5307, totalErrors = 0;
let systemMetrics = {cpu:42, memory:58, disk:45};

// Broadcast function
function broadcast(data) {
  const msg = JSON.stringify(data);
  wss.clients.forEach(client => {
    if (client.readyState === client.OPEN) client.send(msg);
  });
}

// Periodically update metrics
setInterval(() => {
  // randomize agents' metrics
  agents.forEach(a => {
    a.cpu = Math.max(5, Math.min(95, a.cpu + (Math.random()-0.5)*10));
    a.memory = Math.max(20, Math.min(90, a.memory + (Math.random()-0.5)*5));
    a.completed += a.status==='running' ? Math.floor(Math.random()*3) : 0;
    a.uptime = (a.uptime || 90) + 1/3600;
  });
  systemMetrics.cpu = Math.max(10, Math.min(95, systemMetrics.cpu + (Math.random()-0.5)*8));
  systemMetrics.memory = Math.max(20, Math.min(95, systemMetrics.memory + (Math.random()-0.5)*4));
  systemMetrics.disk = Math.max(30, Math.min(95, systemMetrics.disk + (Math.random()-0.3)*2));
  // Broadcast updated metrics to clients
  broadcast({
    type: 'metrics',
    cpu: systemMetrics.cpu.toFixed(1),
    memory: systemMetrics.memory.toFixed(1),
    disk: systemMetrics.disk.toFixed(1),
    agentsActive: agents.filter(a => a.status === 'running').length,
    swarmNodes: swarmNodes.filter(n => n.status==='active').length,
    completed: totalCompleted,
    errors: totalErrors
  });
  
  // Also broadcast agent and swarm data for other tabs
  broadcast({ type:'agents', agents });
  broadcast({ type:'swarm', nodes: swarmNodes });
}, 1000);
```
This snippet shows one way to **simulate live updates**: using `setInterval` to tweak values and broadcast them via WebSocket.  The client code above receives these as `{type:'metrics'}`, `{type:'agents'}`, and `{type:'swarm'}` messages and updates the UI.  You can expand on this to also send pipeline results, test results, or healing events (e.g. by listening for certain `action` messages from the client and then broadcasting new data with `type:'pipelineResult'`, `'testResult'`, or `'healEvent'`).

In essence, the server acts as a simple “agent simulator”.  For example, when it receives a message like `{action: 'runTests'}`, it can generate test results and then call something like `broadcast({type:'testResult', name: ..., status:'pass', duration:..., timestamp:Date.now(), details:...})`【29†L258-L266】【29†L289-L298】. Similarly, a message `{action:'runPipeline', type:'medical'}` can trigger a quick reply `broadcast({type:'pipelineResult', duration:0, ...})`.  

# Bringing It All Together

With these four files in place, run your app by starting the server:

```bash
node server.js
```

This will launch an Express server on port 3001 (binding to `0.0.0.0` to accept external connections).  Navigate to `http://your-server-ip:3001` in a browser – you should see your Master Cockpit UI.  The client’s **app.js** will connect back via WebSocket and begin updating the dashboard in real time.  The UI tabs allow you to initialize the swarm, queue jobs, run pipelines/tests, etc., by sending messages to the server.  The server script receives those WebSocket messages and can adjust its state (or simply echo back) as needed, just as shown in the example WebSocket handler above【29†L258-L266】【29†L289-L298】. 

This four-file setup (one HTML, one CSS, one JS client, one Node server) matches the desired architecture: no React or build step, just a plain Express/WS server and static frontend.  It implements all the requested features—agent metrics, swarm controls, pipeline and test outputs, 48-layer memory display, self-healing events, etc.—using vanilla JavaScript and CSS. The use of Express’s `express.static` and a WebSocket server is well-documented and efficient【22†L63-L72】【25†L258-L264】. 

